how to bury a sutra 11th century japanese pilgrims practices ho center for buddhist studies at stanford skip to main content area home home about the center events people academics research resources partners related links search this site ho center for buddhist studies at stanford how to bury a sutra 11th century japanese pilgrims practices date wed oct 8 2008 5 15pm location encina hall west room 208 program series program series buddhist pilgrimage 2008 09 co sponsor the ho center for buddhist studies the center for east asian studies speaker s name affiliation heather blair indiana mellon postdoctoral fellow religious studies stanford from circa 1000 into the early modern period sutra burial was popular among both clerics and lay people in japan despite widespread archaeological and epigraphical evidence for this practice however we know extremely little about the rituals involved especially during the early history of sutra burial this talk introduces a previously unstudied 11th century source on this topic and explores the ritual process and textual habits that formed and were informed by sutra burial stanford university international comparative & area studies department of religious studies ho center for buddhist studies at stanford stanford university all rights reserved stanford ca 94305 site development by wired moon
